# 四、Band 8 改写版（建议精读）

The bar chart compares the percentages of Australian men and women in six age groups who engaged in regular physical activity in 2010.

Overall, women recorded higher participation rates than men in most age groups, with the exception of those aged 15 to 24. Female participation remained relatively stable at around 50%, whereas the figures for men fluctuated considerably across the different age categories.

Among 15-to-24-year-olds, men recorded the highest level of physical activity, at 52.8%, compared with 47.7% for women. However, in the following age group, the figure for males dropped sharply to 42.2%, while the female rate increased to 48.9%. The gender gap widened further among people aged 35 to 44, with only 39.5% of men engaging in regular exercise, compared with 52.5% of women.

For those aged between 45 and 54, female participation continued to exceed that of males. Women reached a peak of 53.3% in this age group and remained high at 53% among 55-to-64-year-olds. By contrast, the corresponding figures for men were 43.1% and 45.1% respectively. In the oldest age category, the figures for both genders were almost identical, at approximately 47%.

